{{Infobox language family |name=Chapacuran |altname=Chapacura–Wanham |region= |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Wamo–Chapakura languages|Wamo–Chapakúra]] |child1=Madeira |child2=Guapore |map=Chapakuran_languages.png |mapcaption= |glotto=chap1271 |glottorefname=Chapacuran }}
The '''Chapacuran languages''' are a nearly [[Extinct language|extinct]] [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] [[language family]] of [[South America]]. There are three living Chapacuran languages, which are spoken in the southeastern [[Amazon Basin]] of [[Brazil]] and [[Bolivia]].
The Chapacuran languages appear to be related to the extinct [[Wamo language]]. Almost all Chapacuran languages are extinct, and the four that are extant are moribund.
==Languages== Birchall et al. (2013) classify the dozen known Chapacuran languages as follows:<ref>Birchall, Joshua and Dunn, Michael and Greenhill, Simon (2013) ''An internal classification of the Chapacuran language family.''</ref>
*'''Chapacuran''' **Kitemoka&ndash;Tapakura ***[[Chapacura language|Chapacura]] † ***[[Quitemo language|Quitemo]] † **Moreic&ndash;Waric ***Moreic&ndash;Tor ****Nuclear More *****[[Itene language|Itene]] *****[[Cumana language|Cumana]] ****[[Torá language|Torá]] † ***Waric ****Urupa&ndash;Yaru: *****[[Urupa language|Urupa]] † *****Yaru † ****Wanham&ndash;Wari&ndash;Oro Win *****[[Wanham language|Wanham]] † *****Wari&ndash;Oro Win ******[[Oro Win language|Oro Win]] ******[[Wari' language|Wari']] **?[[Napeca language|Napeca]] (Nape) † **?[[Rocorona language|Rocorona]] (Ocorono) †
All languages are rather closely related. Rocorona appears closest to Torá and Moré (Itene), but those do not cluster together in the classification above.
Extinct languages for which Loukotka says 'nothing' is known, but which may have been Chapacuran, include Cujuna, Mataua, Urunumaca, and Herisobocono. Similarities with [[Mure language|Mure]] appear to be loans.<ref name="Glottolog" />
